---
verdict: CIRCLING
rationale: Round 1 reports F1 as "missing blue" (must-contain-blue violated); Round 2 reports F1 as "contains blue" (must-not-contain-blue violated). Round 2's review explicitly acknowledges this is expected oscillation due to mutually exclusive rules in the rubric itself. The same underlying contradiction recurs: fixing one rule violation necessarily creates the other.
---

## Themes

**Mutually exclusive rubric requirements**: The target file is required to simultaneously contain and not contain the word "blue". These contradictory rules force an oscillation between two violations, where each round's fix creates the next round's breaking change. This is not a convergence problem; it is a rubric design problem.

The review explicitly recognizes this pattern and frames it as expected behavior per the rubric's "own description of this oscillation" — indicating that round N and round N+1 will trade violations back and forth indefinitely regardless of implementation correctness.
